    <h2 id="why-vitamin-k2">Why Vitamin K2 Is the Missing Link Between Calcium, Bones, and Heart Health</h2>

    <p>Vitamin K2 solves one of the most overlooked problems in modern nutrition: calcium misdirection. Every year, millions of Americans take calcium and vitamin D supplements for bone health — and the D3 successfully increases calcium absorption by up to 40%. But without vitamin K2, that absorbed calcium has no guidance system. It can deposit in arterial walls (vascular calcification), heart valves, kidneys (kidney stones), and other soft tissues instead of bone matrix. Vitamin K2 activates two critical proteins — osteocalcin and matrix Gla protein — that act as calcium's navigation system, directing it precisely where it is needed and preventing it from accumulating where it is harmful.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">50%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">reduction in arterial calcification and cardiovascular mortality was observed in participants consuming the highest vitamin K2 intake in the landmark Rotterdam Study — a 10-year prospective study of 4,807 adults published in the <em>Journal of Nutrition</em>.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The Rotterdam Study — one of the most significant nutritional epidemiology studies of the 21st century — followed 4,807 Dutch adults for 10 years and found that those consuming the most vitamin K2 (more than 32mcg daily) had a 50% lower risk of arterial calcification, a 50% lower risk of cardiovascular death, and a 25% lower risk of all-cause mortality compared to those with the lowest K2 intake. Critically, vitamin K1 (found in leafy greens) did not show these cardiovascular benefits — the effects were specific to K2.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
