      <cite>Osteoporosis International, 2013 — 244 women, 3-year RCT</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>MK-7 vs. MK-4: Why the Form of K2 Determines Everything</h3>

    <p>Vitamin K2 exists in several forms, but the two that matter for supplementation are MK-7 and MK-4. MK-7 (menaquinone-7) is produced by bacterial fermentation — primarily from natto (fermented soybeans) — and has a long half-life of approximately 72 hours. This means a single daily dose maintains stable blood levels. MK-4 (menaquinone-4) is the form found in animal tissues and has a very short half-life of 1-2 hours. Therapeutic doses of MK-4 range from 15-45mg (15,000-45,000mcg) and must be taken multiple times daily — a dosing regimen that is impractical for gummy supplements. Every product on this list uses MK-7, which is both more practical and better supported by clinical evidence.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Label reading tip:</strong> Look for "MK-7" or "menaquinone-7" on the supplement facts panel. The clinically validated dose is 100-200mcg daily. Products that list "vitamin K2" without specifying MK-7 or MK-4 may use inferior forms. Also check whether D3 is included — the K2 + D3 combination is more effective for bone health than either alone.</p>
    </div>

