    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Vitamin K2: What the Science Says</h4>
      <p>Vitamin K2 is supported by landmark epidemiological studies and multi-year randomized controlled trials demonstrating benefits for both bone and cardiovascular health.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>The Rotterdam Study (Cardiovascular)</strong>
          <p>10-year study of 4,807 adults found highest K2 intake was associated with 50% lower arterial calcification and 50% lower cardiovascular mortality.<br /><em>Journal of Nutrition, 2004</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Bone Mineral Density RCT</strong>
          <p>3-year trial of 244 postmenopausal women found 180mcg MK-7 significantly improved bone mineral density, bone strength, and reduced bone loss at the spine and femoral neck.<br /><em>Osteoporosis International, 2013</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>D3 + K2 Synergy</strong>
          <p>D3 + K2 combination was more effective for bone health than either vitamin alone, directing D3-enhanced calcium absorption into bone matrix rather than soft tissues.<br /><em>Int J Endocrinology, 2017</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>MK-7 vs. MK-4 Bioavailability</strong>
          <p>MK-7's 72-hour half-life allows once-daily dosing at 100-200mcg. MK-4's 1-2 hour half-life requires 15-45mg multiple times daily for equivalent effect.<br /><em>Blood, 2007</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

