    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin K2 Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does vitamin K2 do in the body?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin K2 activates osteocalcin (directing calcium into bones) and matrix Gla protein (preventing calcium from depositing in arteries). It is the critical link between calcium intake and proper calcium distribution in the body.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between MK-7 and MK-4?</summary>
      <p>MK-7 has a 72-hour half-life allowing once-daily dosing at 100-200mcg. MK-4 has only a 1-2 hour half-life requiring 15-45mg multiple times daily. MK-7 is the preferred form for gummy supplements and has the strongest clinical evidence.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why should I take vitamin K2 with vitamin D3?</summary>
      <p>D3 increases calcium absorption by up to 40%. Without K2, that calcium may deposit in arteries instead of bones. K2 directs D3-enhanced calcium into bone matrix. The combination is more effective for bone health than either vitamin alone.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin K2 should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>For MK-7, the clinically studied dose range is 100-200mcg per day. The 3-year bone density trial used 180mcg daily. The Rotterdam Study found benefits at intakes as low as 32mcg. There is no established Upper Intake Level for K2.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does vitamin K2 interact with blood thinners?</summary>
      <p>K2 directly opposes warfarin's mechanism. Do NOT take K2 with warfarin without physician approval. Newer anticoagulants (DOACs like rivaroxaban, apixaban) do not interact with vitamin K and are generally safe to combine with K2.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the signs of vitamin K2 deficiency?</summary>
      <p>K2 deficiency manifests subclinically over years as reduced bone mineralization and increased vascular calcification. Indirect signs include easy bruising, fractures with minimal trauma, and dental cavities. Most Western adults are likely K2-insufficient.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What foods contain vitamin K2?</summary>
      <p>Natto (fermented soybeans) is the richest source at approximately 1,000mcg per serving. Other sources include Gouda cheese, Brie, Edam, egg yolks, and grass-fed butter — but all in much smaller amounts. Most Americans consume very little K2.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is vitamin K2 safe during pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>K2 at standard supplemental doses (100-200mcg MK-7) is generally considered safe during pregnancy. Vitamin K is essential for fetal bone development. However, consult your OB/GYN before starting supplementation, especially if you have clotting disorders.</p>
    </details>

    <!-- WARN BOX -->
